AVIAN INFLUENZA (03): UNITED KINGDOM (NORTHERN IRELAND) POULTRY, SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION, NOT
********************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[ProMED has received the following information from Professor Ian H. Brown, MIBiol PhD, Director of OIE/FAO International Reference Laboratory for Avian Influenza and Newcastle Disease, Weybridge, UK (see 20200124.691319):
Investigations of the suspicious case in poultry in Northern Ireland excluded involvement with notifiable avian influenza (H5 and H7 subtypes) plus Newcastle disease.]

[1]
Date: Wed 8 Jan 2020
Source: BBC News [edited]
https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51011718


The authorities are investigating a suspected case of a notifiable bird disease on a poultry farm in County Fermanagh. It was discovered 4 days ago [4 Jan 2020] when a vet became concerned about increased mortality among the broiler birds.

Tests are being run to see if it is bird flu or another disease called Newcastle disease. It will be several days before final results are back. Restrictions have been put in place on the farm as a precautionary measure.

The Department of Agriculture Environment and Rural Affairs can order the culling of birds to prevent disease spreading. Farmers have been urged to step up their biosecurity.

The disease risk increases in winter with the arrival of migratory birds which can carry them. In recent years bird flu has been confirmed in wild birds on several occasions.

Last month [December 2019], the H5 strain of bird flu was detected at a commercial poultry business in Suffolk; 27 000 chickens were culled there [see commentary].

Poultry is an important part of the Northern Ireland agri-food sector. The latest figures show there are about 26 million birds on farms here. The majority of them are bred for meat, but there are a substantial number of laying hens too. Annual turnover from poultry is about GBP 709 million (USD 928 million) and it employs almost 6000 people.

[Byline: Conor Macauley]

